de.tudarmstadt.ukp.lmf.model.syntax

Class SyntacticArgument

  • java.lang.Object
    • de.tudarmstadt.ukp.lmf.model.abstracts.HasFrequencies
      • de.tudarmstadt.ukp.lmf.model.syntax.SyntacticArgument
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    IHasFrequencies, IHasID, java.lang.Comparable<SyntacticArgument>

    public class SyntacticArgument
extends HasFrequencies
implements IHasID, java.lang.Comparable<SyntacticArgument>
    SyntacticArgument is a class representing an argument of a given SubcategorizationFrame instance. SyntacticArgument allows the connection with a semantic argument by means of a SynSemArgMap instance.
    Author:
    Zijad Maksuti

      • isOptional

        public boolean isOptional()
        Returns true if this SyntacticArgument has the optional attribute set.
        An optional syntactic argument is a complement of a verb (or a noun or an adjective) that can be omitted.

        Example: In the sentence "She paid the bill to her mother", the argument "the bill" is not an optional syntactic argument, because it cannot be omitted: "*She paid to her mother".

        Returns:
        true if the optional attribute is yes, false otherwise

        A preposition type is a node in a hierarchy of prepositions. For example in VerbNet, the preposition type "dir" is subordinated to the preposition type "path"; the preposition type "dir" comprises prepositions such as "across", "along" and "around".

      • getLexeme

        public java.lang.String getLexeme()
        Returns a String representing a lexeme of this SyntacticArgument instance.

        A lexeme is a minimal unit of language which has a semantic interpretation and embodies a distinct cultural concept. In UBY-LMF, a lexeme is not a lexical entry. A lexeme is a pair LexicalEntry / Sense.

        Returns:
        the string representing the lexeme of this syntactic argument or null if the lexeme is not set
